<div id="review_1049329180" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1049329180" />
    <a title="Sean" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13715808-sean"><img alt="Sean" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1605375217p2/13715808.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1049329180?book_show_action=true">Sep 08, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sean" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sean" href="/user/show/13715808-sean">Sean</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781567923735" href="/book/show/3649855-life">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13715808-sean?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13715808-sean?shelf=oulipo">oulipo</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13715808-sean?shelf=available">available</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1049329180" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6187407506396112715">Beyond its status as the Ur-text of encyclopedic maximalism in postmodern literature, or its summation of the Oulipo movement, comprising a stunningly intricate structure of interlocking constraints (most notably the movement of the Knight&apos;s Tour as a formation for the gestalt architecture of the novel), Perec&apos;s crowning work is, at its core, a love letter to art, literature, the humanities—all the while acknowledging (and celebrating) their vacancies of telos outside of aesthetic measures. The </span>
  <span id="freeText6187407506396112715" style="display:none">Beyond its status as the Ur-text of encyclopedic maximalism in postmodern literature, or its summation of the Oulipo movement, comprising a stunningly intricate structure of interlocking constraints (most notably the movement of the Knight's Tour as a formation for the gestalt architecture of the novel), Perec's crowning work is, at its core, a love letter to art, literature, the humanities—all the while acknowledging (and celebrating) their vacancies of telos outside of aesthetic measures. The overarching plot of the novel, interwoven in a fabric of micro-narratives and minutiae, chronicles a wealthy Englishman's lifelong effort to fashion a system of artistic craft which will converge at its own destruction, an explicit attempt of creation-for-itself, resisting any and all applications; so to, Perec's novel can be viewed as a purely aesthetic object, devoid of external meaning, awaiting its own quietus.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6187407506396112715" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


