    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_13701191" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/13701191" />
    <a title="Conor" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/788220-conor"><img alt="Conor" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1202432937p2/788220.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/13701191?book_show_action=true">Jan 27, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Conor" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Conor" href="/user/show/788220-conor">Conor</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/788220-conor?shelf=read-fiction">read-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer13701191" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11641653841087145286">Well, hi there Goodreads! How have you been? It’s been about five months since I’ve reviewed a book. Hopefully that’ll be understandable after the following review.<br/><br/>First off, I’ve been writing an essay. Writing slows down my reading. That’ll be important below.<br/><br/>I’m going to use one of those little spoiler cut lines here. This is my idea of irony, because there’s no plot to spoil, since there&apos;s no plot at all. Oh, there&apos;s characters, and places, but if forty pages were missing from your copy, you </span>
  <span id="freeText11641653841087145286" style="display:none">Well, hi there Goodreads! How have you been? It’s been about five months since I’ve reviewed a book. Hopefully that’ll be understandable after the following review.<br /><br />First off, I’ve been writing an essay. Writing slows down my reading. That’ll be important below.<br /><br />I’m going to use one of those little spoiler cut lines here. This is my idea of irony, because there’s no plot to spoil, since there's no plot at all. Oh, there's characters, and places, but if forty pages were missing from your copy, you wouldn't be in the dark.<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[<br />How nice of you to click.<br /><br />This is a book I read about in a few different places. Given the reviews and the reviewers, I felt like it was a sure to be a good read. The people plugging it are fantastic; Kundera, Calvino, and so on. For them the general feel is that LaUM represents something new in the history of the novel, which it does. <br /><br />Unfortunately, I assume this novel comes from a discussion similar to this one:<br /><br />G. Perec: I am a writer!<br /><br />Guy at party: If you were such a good writer then you could write a novel that has no plot AND no dialog.<br /><br />G. Perec: I...can do that.<br /><br />Guy at party: I bet you a samovar that you cannot.<br /><br />G. Perec: I accept your bet.<br /><br />Guy at party: I will win the samovar! There is no way!<br /><br />G.Perec (several years later): I am now samovar king of samovar mountain!<br /><br />Guy (no longer at party): *weeps into freshly made tea from aforementioned samovar*<br />	<br /><br />…unfortunately, I’m not joking about this whole “lack of plot and dialog” thing. Below is a sample of the text. It contains one of the many, many, lists of things (sometimes really nice things) that are presented in the hundreds of little chapters, most, if not all, are more comparable to sketches than anything, but all of which are tied together by being written as though they are sketches. If there is movement, it is only the sort that could similarly be expressed by lines of motion in a drawing. <br /><br />Here's a sample of the text:<br /><br /><blockquote><br />Cellars. Madame Marcia's cellar.<br />An unbelievable tangle of furniture, objects, and trinkets, and jumble even more inextricable, it would appear, than the muddle reigning in the backroom of her store.<br /><br />Here and there are a few more identifiable objects can be made out amongst the bric-a-brac: a goniometer, a type of articulated wooden protractor, said to belong to the astronomer Nicolas Kratzer, and marinette (the mariner's mate), a magnetized needle pointing to the north and supported by two straws floating on water in a half-full phial, a primitive instrument from which the compass proper, equipped with dial, did not emerge until three centuries later; a ship's desk of English make, fully collapsible, presenting a whole assortment of drawers and flaps; a page from an old herbarium with several specimens of hawkweed (loped hawkweed, Hieracium pilosella, Hieracium aurantiacium, etc.) under a glass plat; an old peanut dispenser, still half-full, with a glass case inscribed with "EXTRA DELICIOUS GOURMET BRAND"; several coffee grinders; seventeen small gold fish with Sanskrit inscriptions; a whole stock of walking sticks and umbrellas; siphons; a weathervane topped by a pretty rusty rooster, a metal washhouse sign, an old tobacconist's carrot-shaped sign; several rectangular, painted biscuit tins: one has an imitation of Gerard's Cupid and Psyche; on another, a Venetian fiesta: masked figures dressed as marquises and marchionesses standing on a floodlit palazzo terrace cheer a brilliantly decorated gondola; in the foreground , perched on one of those painted wooden posts at which watercraft tie up, a little money looks on.....</blockquote><br /><br /><br />I had to cut that off. Can you understand why?<br /><br />Somewhere in the 500 pages of sketches and laundry lists there are some very interesting things, some very pretty descriptions, some <i><b>meta!!!</b></i> things, and some stories (past tense, taking three! pages sometimes) but the total effect is one of apathy. Reading this book was not, as one reviewer described it, like hunting grouse in long grass, but rather like hunting unicorn. The goal of some full story or event is only in the imagination of the hunter. <br /><br />Which brings me to the crux of the review: This book does something new with the novel. Just because you can do something new with art doesn’t mean the end result will be “good” art, or enjoyable at all. I had imagined that this would be the sort of something new that <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/7805.Pale_Fire" title="Pale Fire by Vladimir Nabokov" rel="nofollow noopener">Pale Fire</a> manages, but it's more frustrating than anything. I can accept the idea of abandoning both plot and dialog, and how that might be wonderful in the way that our expectations of a novel and its construction can...but even then, this is an overweight book. <br /><br />Or, if you will: Perec might have aimed to write a book containing all the richness of life in an apartment block, but he manages something that is more like reading a year's worth of newspapers; you can search for further bits of a story you like, but most of the content of the year is unrelated to anything, other than the city that the paper is published in. The total effect is a kind of wallowing in the detritus of life that has already moved on. <br /><br /> <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />That last bit might be some sort of existential point to all of this …if so I can’t remember. It was lost in the static. Frankly, I'd rather read essays about how this book reflects the French drive towards realism than recommend this to anyone.<br /><br />It's not that I didn't enjoy the concept, or the occasionally pretty description, it's just that I had nothing but apathy for the whole of the book. Similar to how you might like something(s) in a catalog without caring about the nature of the catalog as a whole.<br /><br />The upside: it was, for once, more rewarding to work on writing stuff than sit down with a cup of coffee and read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11641653841087145286" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


