    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_5617623" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/5617623" />
    <a title="Nick" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/269132-nick"><img alt="Nick" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1222889972p2/269132.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/5617623?book_show_action=true">Sep 03, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nick" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nick" href="/user/show/269132-nick">Nick</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer5617623" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12788319788785048234">A remarkable achievement. The book captures one moment in an upscale Parisian apartment building, the significance of that instant revealed only at the end. Every chapter describes one of the hundred rooms of the building (with the exception of one cellar), completely frozen in time. Hence, because everything is motionless, much of the book is pure description of books, paintings, chairs, shelves, ceilings, curios, blotters, menus, puzzles, ads, recipes, lists, and much, much more. <br/><br/>Normally, thi</span>
  <span id="freeText12788319788785048234" style="display:none">A remarkable achievement. The book captures one moment in an upscale Parisian apartment building, the significance of that instant revealed only at the end. Every chapter describes one of the hundred rooms of the building (with the exception of one cellar), completely frozen in time. Hence, because everything is motionless, much of the book is pure description of books, paintings, chairs, shelves, ceilings, curios, blotters, menus, puzzles, ads, recipes, lists, and much, much more. <br /><br />Normally, this kind of descriptive writing would be unspeakably boring. For example, try reading the contents of the active and inactive ingredients of your entire medicine cabinet. Yet, almost miraculously, because Perec manages to cover such an incredibly broad range of items while never outstaying his welcome on any individual subject, these vivid details combine to form a beautiful whole.<br /><br />Still, even a collection of lovely images might become mundane stretched over 500 pages. To counter this, in between the lists Perec tells exciting stories of both the objects listed and the inhabitants: a trapeze artist who refused to come down from his wire; a medical researcher swindled by his advisor; a tragic love story between a Polish girl and an Algerian boy; a curious puzzle maker and his revenge. These, and the countless others, are very much page-turners in an old-fashioned sense and perfectly balance the descriptive passages.<br /><br />I had heard that this was an experimental novel and that it was a “puzzle book.” I think what pleased me so much upon actually reading it was that the experiment (a construction of the novel based on a complex matrix of lists shown <a href="http://escarbille.free.fr/vme/?lmn" rel="nofollow noopener"> here</a>) ended up feeling quite natural rather than forced and the world that Perec presented was quite beautiful and touching. It’s both a unique experience and a special one.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12788319788785048234" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


